1
00:00:00,100 --> 00:00:06,075
Today we study conjugate gradient through its geometric meaning: minimizing a quadratic energy.

2
00:00:06,025 --> 00:00:09,350
The algorithm is not just a clever recurrence.

3
00:00:09,350 --> 00:00:15,825
It is a sequence of optimal corrections in the geometry defined by a symmetric positive definite matrix.

4
00:00:15,825 --> 00:00:26,300
For a symmetric positive definite system Ax=b, define phi(x)=\frac12 x^T A x-b^T x.

5
00:00:26,300 --> 00:00:31,025
This function is strictly convex, so it has one global minimizer.

6
00:00:31,025 --> 00:00:36,025
Its gradient is Ax-b, which vanishes exactly when Ax=b.

7
00:00:36,025 --> 00:00:43,150
The residual r_k=b-Ax_k is the negative gradient of the energy at the current iterate.

8
00:00:43,150 --> 00:00:47,850
A large residual means the energy still has a steep direction of descent.

9
00:00:47,850 --> 00:00:51,200
Steepest descent follows the residual direction.

10
00:00:51,200 --> 00:00:55,787
On elongated quadratic contours, this often causes zigzagging.

11
00:00:55,787 --> 00:01:00,300
The method keeps revisiting directions that were already partly corrected.

12
00:01:00,300 --> 00:01:05,800
Conjugate gradient fixes this by using directions that are orthogonal in the A-inner product.

13
00:01:05,800 --> 00:01:16,225
If p_i^T A p_j=0, then minimizing along p_j does not undo the minimization already achieved along p_i.

14
00:01:16,225 --> 00:01:26,037
After k steps, conjugate gradient chooses the best approximation inside x_0+Krylov K_k(A,r_0).

15
00:01:26,037 --> 00:01:32,012
This is the affine space generated by the initial residual and repeated multiplication by A.

16
00:01:32,012 --> 00:01:35,975
The speed of convergence is controlled by spectral geometry.

17
00:01:35,975 --> 00:01:43,262
A smaller condition number gives a better worst-case bound, and clustered eigenvalues can make convergence even faster.

18
00:01:43,262 --> 00:01:52,837
The main message is that conjugate gradient is energy minimization, gradient descent, orthogonalization, and polynomial approximation all at once.

19
00:01:52,837 --> 00:01:59,025
This is why preconditioning is so powerful: it changes the geometry before CG begins.

